                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/249a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-24T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 24, 1912—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Would it be impossible by shipping dynamite through Vera Cruz to the City of
                    Mexico to supply the needs of the mines?</p>
                <p>The President’s proclamation does not affect clothing, dry goods, hardware, and
                    foodstuffs, and Treasury Department has issued orders to its officers on the
                    Mexican border to admit properly invoiced and manifested shipments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
